 or less absolutist justifications for free expression. Contributors examine the aims and effectiveness of government policies, the sometimes contingent ways in which freedom of speech became a reality and a wide range of canonical and non-canonical texts in which contemporaries outlined their ideas and ideals. Overall, the book argues that while the period from 1500 to 1850 witnessed considerable change in terms of both ideas and practices, these were more or less distinct from those that characterise modern debates.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFreedom of speechxHistory. 0aHate speech. 0aReligious pluralism. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / Tudor & Elizabethan Era (1485-1603).2bisacsh  acensorship.  aearly modernity.  afreedom of speech.  afreedom of the press.  alicensing.  amodernity.  apolitical culture.  apolitical ideas.  aprint culture.  asecularisation.1 aBarber, Alex W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarber, Alex W., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBarker, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aComo, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aConti, Greg, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGunther, Karl, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIngram, Robert G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIngram, Robert, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLake, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPaul, Joanne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPeacey, Jason, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPeacey, Jason, eeditor.4ed